entry.title: Deflake AutoDownloadsTest#testAutoDownloadsDialog
entry.content:
It has been observed that the tap on 'allow' (to allow multiple

downloads is ineffective, despite the tap actually happening.

It turns out this is due to tap protection whereby Dialog buttons

won't react to tap events for a short period after they're displayed.

So the multiple downloads never get approved and the second download

never occurs on some bots causing some tests to fail. This CL uses

overrideEnableButtonTapProtectionForTesting to avoid tap protection

disallowing multiple downloads. It also uses the new

hasDownloaded(...) for download verification instead of hasDownload

because hasDownloasd has been found cause flakiness (e.g.

crrev.com/c/4608563.



Testing:

50/50 passes on https://chromium-swarm.appspot.com/task?id=630360be1baa4a10 (previously failing bot).

entry.title: [Code Health Rotation] Mark pointer received as MayBeDangling.
entry.content:
PermissionBubbleMediaAccessHandler uses the following approach to

process incoming media access requests:

- It starts the first one as soon as it receives it.

- It stores next requests.

- Once the first request has been processed, it PostTasks the next one.



In this process, it binds a raw WebContents* as a parameter, and that

WebContents can be destroyed before the PostTask actually runs.



WebContents* lifetime is tracked via a map that holds ongoing request

for this WebContents. When an observer receives the WebContentsDestroyed

message, it instantly removes all mentions of the WebContents from the

map. This is then checked at the beginning of each task. It is in

essence very similar to the example given by the UnsafeDangling<>

documentation.



Other alternatives envisioned:

- Make the call synchronous. This has consequences that are not fully

understood, including by the owning team. It might cause undefined

behavior or segfaults because of other ownership issues.

- Use a RenderFrame based ID instead of raw WebContents* for the

purpose of indexing. This would make things much less natural,

given that multiple connection classes also use raw WebContents*.

On top of that RFH needs multiple IDs for proper tracking, which

is even more inconvenient.



Low-Coverage-Reason: Functional no-op change.

entry.title: Align PrefetchResponseReader with SinglePrefetch
entry.content:
This CL aligns the indexing of PrefetchResponseReader

and PrefetchContainer::SinglePrefetch, by splitting

a PrefetchResponseReader spanning multiple redirect hops

into multiple PrefetchResponseReaders.

To clarify this alignment, this CL moves the ownership of

PrefetchResponseReader to SinglePrefetch.



Before this CL, multiple redirect hops within

a PrefetchResponseReader were separated by

pause_after_event=true items in `event_queue_`.

A PrefetchResponseReader paused, disconnected and

rebound mojo clients on the redirect hop boundaries.



After this CL, a PrefetchResponseReader only serves

a single redirect hop and is bound to a mojo client

only once.

Multiple PrefetchResponseReaders can be filled by a

single PrefetchStreamingURLLoader, and are switched

via SetResponseReader() each time a redirect is received.

entry.title: Add reporting of statistics for AllocationTraceRecorder
entry.content:
This CL introduces collection of statistics to the

AllocationTraceRecorder and periodic printing of these.



When MTE is enabled in synchronous mode, the AllocationTraceRecorder is

invoked upon each allocation or free. Therefore, its performance is

quite critical. To better understand certain properties like number of

allocations or number of collisions, we introduce a simple reporting

mechanism. This includes collection of additional information and

periodic output of the collected data. Since gathering the data incurs

a runtime overhead, we disable the feature by default.

entry.title: [//media] CHECK external sampling isn't passed to ReadbackTexturePlane
entry.content:
ReadbackTexturePlaneToMemorySyncOOP() checks the SharedImageFormatType

of the input VideoFrame to determine how to copy the texture for the

desired plane. Reading back individual planes is not possible when using

external sampling, and indeed this code implicitly assumes that input

legacy multiplanar SharedImages aren't using external sampling:



- It DCHECKs that |src_frame.mailbox_holder(src_plane)| is not zero,

which will be false when using external sampling if `src_plane` is > 0

- Every callsite of this method (via ReadbackTexturePlaneToMemorySync())

calls it in a loop over all planes). In the case of Blink this is all

planes of the destination format rather than information from the source

VideoFrame itself; nonetheless, that destination format must be the same

underlying format as that of the texture since no conversion is done.

Thus, those destination formats will themselves have > 1 plane in the

case where the SharedImage is legacy multiplanar.



This CL adds a CHECK that the video frame does not require external

sampling to make this restriction explicit.

entry.title: Eliminate the manual ChromeDriver release process
entry.content:
As of M115, ChromeDriver is fully integrated into the Chrome release

process. Across all release channels (Stable, Beta, Dev, Canary),

every Chrome release that gets pushed to users automatically gets a

correspondingly-versioned ChromeDriver release, available for

download via Chrome for Testing infrastructure [1].



This significantly simplifies the status quo & solves a number of

issues:



1. It completely eliminates the manual ChromeDriver release process.

2. It aligns ChromeDriver releases with Chrome releases.

3. It makes it significantly easier for users to download matching

Chrome for Testing + ChromeDriver binaries.



This patch removes any scripts and references to the old ChromeDriver

release process.



Announcement: https://groups.google.com/g/chromedriver-users/c/clpipqvOGjE



[1]: https://googlechromelabs.github.io/chrome-for-testing/

entry.title: PreloadingDevTools: Add holdbacks by PreloadingConfig to Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated

Historically, preloading was controlled by coarse-grained feature flags

PreloadingHoldback/Prerender2Holdback. We introduced PreloadingConfig

[1] and we are adopting more fine-grained control. For more details,

see [2] and [3].

disabledByHoldbackPrerenderSpeculationRules to the CDP event

Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated.



Note that by historical reason, DevTools frontend had gotten holdback

status with SystemInfo.getFeatureState [4]. This CL aggregates

"disabled" reasons to Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated and allows

DevTools frontend to listen only the event once we deprecate the old

flags.

entry.title: Incognito Reauth: Fix reauth screen not restored when activity is killed
entry.content:
Under memory pressure (emulated by the "Don't keep activities" setting), IncognitoReauthController gets killed after starting the reauthentication flow. When restored, savedInstanceState is checked for incognitoReauthPending when re-initializing the IncognitoReauthController, to determine whether to resume the reauthentication flow.



The problem lies when the SavedInstanceState is reset in

ChromeTabbedActivity::onStartWithNative which sets it to null before it

is checked for the incognitoReauthPending key in

RootUiCoordinator::onFinishNativeInitialization, making

mIsIncognitoReauthPendingOnRestore in IncognitoReauthController always

return false and the reauth screen not getting restored when the

activity is killed.



This CL saves the incognitoReauthPending key value from

SavedInstanceState in the the constructor of RootUiCoordinator before

it is reset.
